                    <div class="col-lg-12 col-md-12 text-center image-height"><img src="~/images/twowheeler/upcomming/2025/suzuki gsx/black.webp" alt="black" title="black" loading="lazy" /></div>
                </div>

                <p>The core of the Suzuki GSX-8S is its brand-new parallel-twin engine. This is a significant departure from Suzuki's past middleweight offerings and is a clear sign of the company's commitment to modern engineering. The motorcycle is powered by a <span class="font-weight-700">776cc, </span> four-stroke, liquid-cooled, DOHC parallel-twin engine. This engine features a <span class="font-weight-700">270-degree crankshaft, </span>which gives it a distinct, V-twin-like exhaust note and a punchy, torque-rich power delivery. </p>
                <p>The engine is tuned to produce a very healthy<span class="font-weight-700"> 83 bhp</span> of peak power at<span class="font-weight-700"> 8,500 rpm</span> and a maximum torque of <span class="font-weight-700">78 Nm at 6,800 rpm. </span>This power and torque combination ensures that the GSX-8S is not only fast but also incredibly tractable and easy to ride in a variety of conditions, from city traffic to winding mountain roads. The bike comes with a smooth six-speed gearbox and a bi-directional quickshifter as standard, a feature that is a huge plus and adds to the thrill of riding. <p>
                <p>In terms of chassis, the <span class="font-weight-700">GSX-8S </span>is built on a robust steel backbone frame, which is designed to provide excellent rigidity and feel. The suspension setup is handled by 41mm KYB inverted front forks and a link-type monoshock at the rear. While not fully adjustable, this setup is tuned for a good balance of comfort and sporty handling. The braking system is handled by Nissin radial-mount calipers gripping <span class="font-weight-700">twin 310mm discs </span>at the front and a single 240mm disc at the rear, both equipped with a dual-channel ABS. </p>
                <p>Here is a detailed look at the expected specifications: </p>
